The `frappe.msgprint` function is used to display a message in a modal dialog. You can pass a string as the message, or you can pass an object with the following properties:

* `title`: The title of the modal dialog.
* `message`: The message to be displayed in the modal dialog.
* `indicator`: The indicator to be shown in the modal dialog (e.g., 'green', 'red', 'blue').

Here are some examples of how to use `frappe.msgprint`:

```javascript
// Only message
frappe.msgprint(__('Document updated successfully'));

// With options
frappe.msgprint({
  title: __('Notification'),
  indicator: 'green',
  message: __('Document updated successfully')
});
```

You can bind a primary action to a `frappe.msgprint` dialog to show a confirmation dialog.  The primary action can contain either a `server_action` or a `client_action` which are dotted paths to the respective methods that will execute on clicking the primary button. Here's an example:

```javascript
frappe.msgprint({
  title: __('Notification'),
  message: __('Are you sure you want to proceed?'),
  primary_action: {
    'label': 'Proceed',
    // either one of the actions can be passed
    'server_action': 'dotted.path.to.method',
    'client_action': 'dotted_path.to_method',
    'args': args
  }
});
```

This code will create a confirmation dialog with the message 'Are you sure you want to proceed?' and a 'Proceed' button. Clicking the 'Proceed' button will execute the specified `server_action` or `client_action`.

The `frappe.prompt` function is used to prompt the user for a value or list of values. You can pass a label, a field definition (df), or a list of fields as arguments to the function. Here are some examples:

